This paper is primarily focused on robotic manipulation tasks, which falls under the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The paper also heavily utilizes machine learning techniques such as reinforcement learning and imitation learning, which are commonly found in the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The use of deep neural networks for training skills and policies suggests that the paper may also fall under the machine learning (cs.LG) and computer vision (cs.CV) sub-categories. Finally, the paper's focus on training policies for robotic manipulation tasks suggests that it may also fall under the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category.
